<BODY>

<p>
The <a href="glindex.html#LDM">LDM</a> system has a registry for configuration
and runtime parameters that is similar to Java preferences, the Windows
registry, or GNU GConf.  The parameters of the registry and their
values can be viewed by executing the command "<a
href="glindex.html#regutil"><tt>regutil</tt></a>".

<p>
The parameters are

<blockquote>
<table align="center" border="2" cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0">
    <tr>
	<th>Parameter Pathname</th>
	<th>Value Description</th>
	<th>Default Value</th>
    </tr>
    <tr>
	<td nowrap><tt>@REG_QUEUE_PATH@</tt></td>
	<td>The path name of the 
            <a href="glindex.html#product-queue">product-queue</a>
        </td>
        <td nowrap><tt>$LDMHOME/var/queue/ldm.pq</tt></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
	<td nowrap><tt>@REG_QUEUE_SIZE@</tt></td>
	<td>The size of the
            <a href="glindex.html#product-queue">product-queue</a>
            in bytes.  The suffixes <tt>K</tt>, <tt>M</tt>, and <tt>G</tt> may
            be used for "kilo", "mega" and "giga", respectively.
        </td>
        <td nowrap><tt>@REG_QUEUE_SIZE_DEFAULT@</tt></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
	<td nowrap><tt>@REG_QUEUE_SLOTS@</tt></td>
	<td>The capacity of the
            <a href="glindex.html#product-queue">product-queue</a>
            in terms of the maximum number of data-products that it can hold.
            Specified as a number or as the string <tt>default</tt> (in 
            which case the number of slots is automatically computed based
            on an assumed mean size for the data-products).
        </td>
        <td nowrap><tt>@REG_QUEUE_SLOTS_DEFAULT@</tt></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
	<td nowrap><tt>@REG_SURFQUEUE_SIZE@</tt></td>
	<td>The size of the
            <a href="glindex.html#pqsurf">pqsurf</a>
            queue in bytes.  The suffixes <tt>K</tt>, <tt>M</tt>, and
            <tt>G</tt> may be used for "kilo", "mega" and "giga", respectively.
        </td>
        <td nowrap><tt>@REG_SURFQUEUE_SIZE_DEFAULT@</tt></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
	<td nowrap><tt>@REG_HOSTNAME@</tt></td>
	<td>The fully-qualified name of the computer on which the LDM runs
    </tr>
    <tr>
	<td nowrap><tt>@REG_LOG_FILE@</tt></td>
	<td>Pathname of the LDM log file</td>
        <td nowrap><tt>$LDMHOME/var/logs/ldmd.log</tt></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
	<td nowrap><tt>@REG_LOG_COUNT@</tt></td>
	<td>The number of LDM log files to keep around</td>
        <td nowrap><tt>@REG_LOG_COUNT_DEFAULT@</tt></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
	<td nowrap><tt>@REG_LOG_ROTATE@</tt></td>
	<td>Whether or not the command <tt>ldmadmin start</tt> should start a
            new log file.  Zero means no; non-zero means yes.</td>
        <td nowrap><tt>@REG_LOG_ROTATE_DEFAULT@</tt></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
	<td nowrap><tt>@REG_METRICS_COUNT@</tt></td>
	<td>The number of LDM metrics files to keep around</td>
        <td nowrap><tt>@REG_METRICS_COUNT_DEFAULT@</tt></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
	<td nowrap><tt>@REG_METRICS_FILES@</tt></td>
	<td>The number of LDM metrics files to keep around</td>
        <td nowrap><tt>$LDMHOME/var/logs/metrics.txt*</tt></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
	<td nowrap><tt>@REG_IP_ADDR@</tt></td>
	<td>The IP address of the interface on which the LDM server should
            listen for incoming connections.  An address of <tt>0.0.0.0</tt>
            will cause the server to listen on all available interfaces.</td>
        <td nowrap><tt>@REG_IP_ADDR_DEFAULT@</tt></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
	<td nowrap><tt>@REG_PORT@</tt></td>
	<td>The number of the port on which the LDM server should
            listen for incoming connections</td>
        <td nowrap><tt>@REG_PORT_DEFAULT@</tt></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
	<td nowrap><tt>@REG_MAX_CLIENTS@</tt></td>
	<td>The maximum number of remotely-initiated connections the LDM
            server should allow before ignoring additional remotely-initiated
            connection attempts</td>
        <td nowrap><tt>@REG_MAX_CLIENTS_DEFAULT@</tt></td>
    </tr>
</table>
</blockquote>

</BODY>
